{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496397"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:46:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:46:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1353"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1353"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.01,0.23,0.02,0.38]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1353"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58920"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1353"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1353"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44330"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"782"},{"type":"tags","id":"1186"},{"type":"tags","id":"1272"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"6292"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4126"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4271"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36281"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43075"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58920"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with sudden onset right arm pain after weightlifting at the gym. While performing an upper body exercise, he felt a sharp pain and audible \u0027pop\u0027 in his right arm. He has noticed a visible lump in his upper arm since the injury. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He is an ex-professional basketball player.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is an obvious bulge in the right upper arm (Image). The area is tender to palpation. He has full range of movement at the shoulder and elbow joints. Distal neurovascular examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate method to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound","Fine needle aspiration cytology","Magnetic resonance imaging","Computed tomography","Elbow flexion against resistance"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad for rupture of the long head of biceps tendon: acute pain during activity, an audible \u0027pop\u0027, and visible deformity. The diagnosis is primarily clinical, with \u003Cstrong\u003Eelbow flexion against resistance\u003C/strong\u003E being the key diagnostic test. During this manoeuvre, the examiner will observe the characteristic \u0027pop-eye\u0027 deformity as the muscle belly bunches up proximally in the arm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound\u003C/strong\u003E can visualise the retracted tendon and is a cost-effective imaging option, but is typically unnecessary when the clinical presentation is classic, as in this case. The accuracy of ultrasound is also operator-dependent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging\u003C/strong\u003E provides excellent soft tissue detail and is the most accurate imaging modality for confirming biceps tendon pathology. However, it is expensive and unnecessary for diagnosis when clinical findings are clear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography\u003C/strong\u003E provides poor soft tissue differentiation compared to MRI and is not indicated for isolated biceps tendon injuries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration cytology\u003C/strong\u003E has no role in diagnosing tendon ruptures and could potentially cause harm to surrounding structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment is typically conservative in older patients, focusing on analgesia and rehabilitation. Surgical repair may be considered in younger, active patients or those with significant functional demands.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A ruptured long head of biceps tendon typically presents with acute pain, a \u0027pop-eye\u0027 deformity, and weakness of elbow flexion.","Clinical examination with resisted elbow flexion is sufficient to diagnose biceps tendon rupture in most cases.","Imaging is rarely required but MRI is the most accurate modality if diagnostic uncertainty exists."],"references":["Sarmento M. Long head of biceps: from anatomy to treatment. Acta Reumatol Port. 2015;40(1):26-33. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25351662/","Nho SJ, Strauss EJ, Lenart BA, Provencher MT, Mazzocca AD, Verma NN, et al. Long head of the biceps tendinopathy: diagnosis and management. J Am Acad Orthop Surg. 2010;18(11):645-56. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21041799/","Lynch J, Yu CC, Chen C, Muh S. Magnetic resonance imaging versus ultrasound in diagnosis of distal biceps tendon avulsion. Orthop Traumatol Surg Res. 2019 Sep;105(5):861-866. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30987955/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44330"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1353"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15939"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15939"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0893cdcf-5b5c-465e-9b32-0e088bc7e677.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0893cdcf-5b5c-465e-9b32-0e088bc7e677.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44330"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-03T20:53:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-03T20:57:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1353"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58920"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"41","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/41"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc80","name":"Anatomy","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null}